		<div id="qualification">
			<h2>Qualification Criteria</h2>
			<p>For an entry to qualify and earn you points towards winning an award, it must meet all of the following criteria. <a href="/attachments/contest_checklist.pdf" target="_blank">Download</a> a one-page qualification check list to hand out to your students.  
				<ol>
					<li><p>It must be a math <strong>WORD problem</strong>, NOT a straightforward equation such as “x +3 = 5, what is x?”</p></li>
					<li><p>It must be a <strong>multistep</strong> problem whose solution requires 2 or more steps. Multistep means varied operations. If a problem repeats the same operation multiple times, it is counted as a one-step problem. For example, the following problem is counted as a 1-step problem because it simply repeats addition twice: “Sarah ate 500 calories for breakfast, 600 calories for lunch, and 700 calories for dinner, how many calories did she eat in all?”</p></li>
					<li><p>It must be <strong>at or above the author’s grade level</strong> based on the Common Core State standards. For example: if the author is an 8th-grade student but his/her question is at the 7th-grade level or lower, not only the question will be disqualified, but also the author will lose publication credits as a penalty. If his/her publication credit balance drops to zero, he/she can no longer submit any more question into the contest, nor can he/she publish any more posts on Shooloo.</p><p> For every grade his/her submission is below his/her grade level, he/she loses 10 points of publication credit. For example, if an 8th-grade student submits a 1st-grade question, he/she will lose 70 points of publication credit. Conversely, if his/her question is at or above his/her grade level, he/she will gain 20 points of publication credit as a bonus. </p></li>
					<li><p>Its answer must be <strong>mathematically correct</strong> and include a <strong>step-by-step explanation</strong> of its solution as shown in the <a href="#sample">sample problems</a>.</p></li>
					<li><p>Its question and answer must be <strong>grammatically correct with no spelling errors.</strong></p></li>
					<li><p>Its question must be <strong>clear, concise,</strong> and give enough information to arrive at an answer. </p></li>
					<li><p>It must be related to the topic of <strong>healthy-eating</strong>. For example, the following question is about eating but not healthy eating: “I ate 5 burgers every day in the past week. How many burgers did I eat in all?”</p><p> In contrast, the following question is about healthy-eating: “A burger has 900 calories, vs. a salad has 300 calories. How many fewer calories do I take in if I eat a salad instead of a burger?” </p></li>
					<li><p>Its content must be <strong>appropriate</strong>. It must NOT contain any of the following:
						<ul>
							<li><p>Watermarked images.</p></li>
							<li><p>Racial or cultural discrimination.</p></li>
							<li><p>Personal information, including any participants’ real names, school affiliation, phone numbers, or emails. </p></li>
							<li><p>Offensive or derogatory remarks. For example, it is not OK to say in a problem, “You are fat and should shed 50 pounds.” But it is OK to say, “I am overweighed and need to lose some weight.” The rule of the thumb is: if it is something that you don’t want anyone else to say about you, you shouldn’t say it about anyone else on Shooloo.</p></li>
							<li><p>Plagiarized content or content that infringes on the intellectual property of others. For example, a student shouldn’t copy the <a href="#sample">sample problems</a> verbatim without much change beyond the numbers or product names and submit them as his/her own entries.</p></li>
						</ul>
					</p></li>
					<li><p>Its content must be <strong>realistic</strong>. Students should conduct research on relevant data instead of plucking numbers out of thin air. For example: it is unrealistic to say, “I burnt 1,000,000,000,000 calories for every mile I walked”.</p></li>
					<li><p>It must reflect the author’s own <strong>research and original thinking</strong>. It should not be essentially the same problems as the ones already published on Shooloo. For example, the following two questions are essentially the same. “I ate 1/3 of an apple in the morning and ½ of the apple in the afternoon. What fraction of an apple did I eat in all?”  “I ate 1/3 of an orange in the morning and ¼ of an orange in the afternoon. What fraction of an orange did I eat in all?”</p></li>
				</ol>
			</p>
